{"type":"text","timestamp":1780728111449,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"id":"prt_e9baa8146001dvO0BnMDkuqTdM","messageID":"msg_e9baa6841001Ctocor307bFP0E","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","type":"text","text":"The worker confirms event-driven embedding with content-hash reuse and best-effort back-channel events; I’m reading only the remaining persistence/re-embed handlers needed to cite the idempotency and hint-driven re-embed flow.","time":{"start":1780728103238,"end":1780728111447},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0b889e1f3f36b228016a23c127373881919468d20e7bc88a09","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728111498,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_DBwyKUpMqoZdINH5JI6MNdSG","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py","offset":359,"limit":270},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n359: def _build_patch(\n360:     result: EnrichmentResult,\n361:     agent_provided_fields: list[str] | None = None,\n362: ) -> dict:\n363:     \"\"\"Translate an ``EnrichmentResult`` into the storage PATCH body.\n364: \n365:     ORM-column fields go at the top level; metadata fields land under\n366:     ``metadata_patch`` for the storage layer's atomic JSONB merge.\n367: \n368:     ``agent_provided_fields`` is the publisher's snapshot of which\n369:     columns the agent set explicitly at write time. Those fields are\n370:     excluded from the PATCH so a redelivery (or a slow worker run)\n371:     can't downgrade an agent-provided ``weight=0.9`` back to\n372:     ``EnrichmentResult.weight``'s default of ``0.7``. Critical because\n373:     Pydantic defaults survive ``exclude_none=True`` — every event\n374:     technically carries values for ``memory_type``, ``weight``,\n375:     ``status``.\n376: \n377:     ``ts_valid_*`` are emitted as ISO strings (``model_dump(mode=\"json\")``).\n378:     asyncpg requires datetime instances for ``DateTime(timezone=True)``\n379:     columns and rejects ISO strings with ``CannotCoerceError``, so the\n380:     storage layer's ``PATCH /memories/{id}`` route calls\n381:     ``_parse_datetimes(body)`` at the API boundary to coerce these\n382:     fields before the SQL UPDATE runs (mirrors the POST route's\n383:     pre-existing parse step). Keeping the worker's payload as ISO\n384:     strings keeps it JSON-serialisable end-to-end (httpx ``json=``\n385:     falls back to stdlib ``json.dumps`` which can't serialise\n386:     ``datetime``); the coercion lives at the storage boundary\n387:     rather than per-publisher. This was a real production bug\n388:     until 2026-04-26 — see PR <CAURA-595-ts-valid-iso-coercion>.\n389:     \"\"\"\n390:     skip = frozenset(agent_provided_fields or ())\n391:     dump = result.model_dump(mode=\"json\", exclude_none=True)\n392: \n393:     # ``ts_valid_*`` are semantically meaningful as ``None`` (\"this\n394:     # memory has no validity bounds\"), distinct from \"field absent\".\n395:     # ``exclude_none=True`` would silently drop them, leaving stale\n396:     # dates from a prior enrichment run intact in storage. Preserve\n397:     # them explicitly so a re-delivery (or a different LLM run that\n398:     # doesn't infer dates) can clear what an earlier run wrote.\n399:     #\n400:     # GUARD: only null-patch when the result came from a real LLM\n401:     # call (``llm_ms > 0``). The heuristic fallback (``fake_enrich``\n402:     # — used when the configured provider fails after retries +\n403:     # fallback chain exhausts) NEVER infers dates, so its absence of\n404:     # ``ts_valid_*`` is \"I don't know\", not \"no bounds\". Without this\n405:     # guard, a Pub/Sub redelivery that coincides with an LLM outage\n406:     # would land on the heuristic and wipe temporal bounds a prior\n407:     # successful run wrote — silent data loss with no log surface.\n408:     if result.llm_ms > 0:\n409:         for ts_field in (\"ts_valid_start\", \"ts_valid_end\"):\n410:             if ts_field not in skip and ts_field not in dump:\n411:                 dump[ts_field] = None\n412: \n413:     patch: dict = {}\n414:     for field in _ENRICHMENT_ORM_FIELDS:\n415:         if field in skip:\n416:             continue\n417:         if field in dump:\n418:             value = dump[field]\n419:             # Empty title from the LLM (or from ``fake_enrich`` for\n420:             # very short content) shouldn't clobber a previously-\n421:             # stored valid title. Other ORM fields (``memory_type``,\n422:             # ``weight``, ``status``) have schema defaults that\n423:             # ``EnrichmentResult`` always emits — those go through\n424:             # ``agent_provided_fields`` for the gate. ``title`` has\n425:             # no agent-side counterpart (it's enricher-only output)\n426:             # and no useful default — empty == \"didn't infer\".\n427:             if field == \"title\" and value == \"\":\n428:                 continue\n429:             patch[field] = value\n430: \n431:     # The hot-path writer set ``metadata.enrichment_pending=true`` when\n432:     # deferring; clear it unconditionally on every successful worker\n433:     # PATCH so a read-after-success returns clean state. Pre-seeds the\n434:     # patch dict so the ``if metadata_patch:`` gate below always fires\n435:     # (when heuristic fallback produces no real metadata fields, this\n436:     # seed ensures the PATCH still goes out and clears the stale flag\n437:     # — without it, a fallback redelivery would silently keep the row\n438:     # marked pending forever). Storage's JSONB ``||`` merge overwrites\n439:     # a prior ``True`` with ``False`` cleanly.\n440:     metadata_patch: dict = {\"enrichment_pending\": False}\n441:     for field in _ENRICHMENT_METADATA_FIELDS:\n442:         if field in skip:\n443:             continue\n444:         value = dump.get(field)\n445:         if field in _ENRICHMENT_ALWAYS_WRITE_METADATA:\n446:             # Same ``llm_ms > 0`` guard as ``ts_valid_*`` above:\n447:             # ``fake_enrich`` returns ``contains_pii=False``,\n448:             # ``pii_types=[]``, ``tags=[]``, ``retrieval_hint=\"\"`` as\n449:             # Pydantic defaults — all non-None. Without this guard, a\n450:             # heuristic-fallback redelivery (LLM outage during a\n451:             # storage 5xx retry) would clobber real LLM-produced PII\n452:             # detection + recall hints + tags that an earlier\n453:             # successful run wrote. The ``llm_ms > 0`` proxy is the\n454:             # same one ``ts_valid_*`` uses; ``fake_enrich`` hard-codes\n455:             # ``llm_ms=0`` so the proxy is reliable.\n456:             if result.llm_ms > 0 and value is not None:\n457:                 metadata_patch[field] = value\n458:             continue\n459:         # Other metadata fields: drop the specific defaults that carry\n460:         # no information — heuristic-fallback ``\"summary\": \"\"``,\n461:         # ``\"llm_ms\": 0`` from early-return paths. Listed by value\n462:         # rather than a blanket ``if not value`` so a future\n463:         # ``dict``-typed field isn't accidentally silenced.\n464:         if value is None or value in (False, 0, \"\", []):\n465:             continue\n466:         metadata_patch[field] = value\n467:     if metadata_patch:\n468:         patch[\"metadata_patch\"] = metadata_patch\n469: \n470:     return patch\n471: \n472: \n473: async def handle_enrich_request(event: Event) -> None:\n474:     \"\"\"Process a single enrich-request event.\n475: \n476:     Mirrors :func:`handle_embed_request`'s shape: validate → reconstruct\n477:     tenant config → run enricher (3-tier fallback inside\n478:     ``common.enrichment.enrich_memory``) → PATCH result onto the row.\n479:     \"\"\"\n480:     try:\n481:         request = MemoryEnrichRequest(**event.payload)\n482:     except ValidationError:\n483:         logger.exception(\n484:             \"dropping malformed enrich-request payload\",\n485:             extra={\n486:                 \"event_type\": event.event_type,\n487:                 \"event_id\": str(event.event_id),\n488:                 \"dropped\": True,\n489:             },\n490:         )\n491:         return\n492: \n493:     if _storage_client_factory is None:\n494:         logger.error(\n495:             \"dropping enrich-request: consumer not configured\",\n496:             extra={\n497:                 \"event_id\": str(event.event_id),\n498:                 \"memory_id\": str(request.memory_id),\n499:                 \"dropped\": True,\n500:             },\n501:         )\n502:         return\n503: \n504:     storage = _storage_client_factory()\n505:     tenant_config = _build_tenant_config(request)\n506: \n507:     reference_dt = datetime.fromisoformat(request.reference_datetime) if request.reference_datetime else None\n508: \n509:     # ``enrich_memory`` never raises — it falls through to the keyword\n510:     # heuristic (``fake_enrich``) on every error path. So a transient\n511:     # provider failure can't nack-loop the subscription.\n512:     result = await enrich_memory(\n513:         request.content,\n514:         tenant_config,\n515:         reference_datetime=reference_dt,\n516:     )\n517: \n518:     patch = _build_patch(result, request.agent_provided_fields)\n519: \n520:     # Surface the sync-vs-async behavioural gap: the synchronous write\n521:     # path in ``memory_service.py`` fans ``atomic_facts`` out into\n522:     # child memories. The async worker doesn't yet — content with\n523:     # multiple distinct claims gets fewer memories on this path.\n524:     # Implementing child-memory creation in the worker requires a\n525:     # fresh embed roundtrip per child + a parent-link plumb through\n526:     # storage; tracked separately.\n527:     #\n528:     # Logged at WARNING (not ERROR): the gap is real but expected\n529:     # under the current PR scope, and ERROR-paging on every multi-fact\n530:     # write would drown the on-call alert channel without giving them\n531:     # an actionable fix. The follow-up ticket reference makes the gap\n532:     # discoverable; a dashboard counter on the WARNING string lets\n533:     # operators quantify exposure.\n534:     if result.atomic_facts:\n535:         logger.warning(\n536:             \"enrich-request for memory %s produced %d atomic_facts; \"\n537:             \"child-memory creation not yet implemented in async path \"\n538:             \"(tracked: CAURA-595 follow-up) — secondary facts will \"\n539:             \"NOT appear as child memories\",\n540:             request.memory_id,\n541:             len(result.atomic_facts),\n542:         )\n543: \n544:     # Per-tenant slot scoped to the PATCH only; matches the embed\n545:     # consumer above. The LLM enrichment call upstream is the\n546:     # expensive step but doesn't touch the storage-writer pool.\n547:     async with per_tenant_storage_slot(request.tenant_id):\n548:         await update_memory_enrichment(\n549:             storage,\n550:             memory_id=request.memory_id,\n551:             tenant_id=request.tenant_id,\n552:             fields=patch,\n553:         )\n554: \n555:     # Back-channel: announce successful enrichment so core-api (or any\n556:     # other subscriber) can react. Best-effort — a publish failure\n557:     # MUST NOT nack the upstream PATCH that already succeeded; the\n558:     # enrichment is durable in storage either way. ``logger.exception``\n559:     # captures the failure for alerting; the consumer returns\n560:     # successfully so Pub/Sub acks the input event.\n561:     try:\n562:         await publish_memory_enriched(\n563:             memory_id=request.memory_id,\n564:             tenant_id=request.tenant_id,\n565:             content=request.content,\n566:             retrieval_hint=result.retrieval_hint or \"\",\n567:         )\n568:     except Exception:\n569:         logger.exception(\n570:             \"enriched back-channel publish failed; ack-continuing\",\n571:             extra={\n572:                 \"memory_id\": str(request.memory_id),\n573:                 \"tenant_id\": request.tenant_id,\n574:             },\n575:         )\n576: \n577:     logger.info(\n578:         \"enrich-request processed\",\n579:         extra={\n580:             \"memory_id\": str(request.memory_id),\n581:             \"tenant_id\": request.tenant_id,\n582:             \"provider\": request.enrichment_provider or \"platform\",\n583:             \"memory_type\": result.memory_type,\n584:             \"llm_ms\": result.llm_ms,\n585:         },\n586:     )\n587: \n588: \n589: class _SuppressionAdapter(SuppressionStorageAdapter):\n590:     \"\"\"Thin adapter wiring :func:`upsert_tenant_suppression` into the\n591:     shared :class:`SuppressionStorageAdapter` contract (CAURA-694).\n592: \n593:     Lives in the consumer module rather than ``clients/`` so the lazy\n594:     storage-client lookup (``_storage_client_factory``) stays bound to\n595:     the consumer's ``configure`` entry point — same pattern the embed\n596:     + enrich handlers use to reach the storage client.\n597:     \"\"\"\n598: \n599:     async def set_tenant_suppression(self, *, tenant_id: str, action: str, updated_by: str | None) -> None:\n600:         if _storage_client_factory is None:\n601:             raise RuntimeError(\"consumer.configure() must run before register_consumers()\")\n602:         client = _storage_client_factory()\n603:         await upsert_tenant_suppression(\n604:             client,\n605:             tenant_id=tenant_id,\n606:             action=action,\n607:             updated_by=updated_by,\n608:         )\n609: \n610: \n611: def register_consumers() -> None:\n612:     \"\"\"Wire the consumers into the event bus.\n613: \n614:     Called once at app startup, before ``bus.start()`` — the Pub/Sub\n615:     backend spawns its pull loops in ``start()`` based on the current\n616:     handler registry, so a late ``subscribe()`` would silently orphan\n617:     the handler.\n618:     \"\"\"\n619:     bus = get_event_bus()\n620:     bus.subscribe(Topics.Memory.EMBED_REQUESTED, handle_embed_request)\n621:     bus.subscribe(Topics.Memory.ENRICH_REQUESTED, handle_enrich_request)\n622:     # CAURA-694: register the org-suppression mirror handler. Subscribing\n623:     # here keeps the registration order single-file rather than scattered\n624:     # across multiple ``register_*`` entry points.\n625:     register_suppression_consumer(_SuppressionAdapter())\n\n(End of file - total 625 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"def _build_patch(\n    result: EnrichmentResult,\n    agent_provided_fields: list[str] | None = None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Translate an ``EnrichmentResult`` into the storage PATCH body.\n\n    ORM-column fields go at the top level; metadata fields land under\n    ``metadata_patch`` for the storage layer's atomic JSONB merge.\n\n    ``agent_provided_fields`` is the publisher's snapshot of which\n    columns the agent set explicitly at write time. Those fields are\n    excluded from the PATCH so a redelivery (or a slow worker run)\n    can't downgrade an agent-provided ``weight=0.9`` back to\n    ``EnrichmentResult.weight``'s default of ``0.7``. Critical because\n    Pydantic defaults survive ``exclude_none=True`` — every event\n    technically carries values for ``memory_type``, ``weight``,\n    ``status``.\n\n    ``ts_valid_*`` are emitted as ISO strings (``model_dump(mode=\"json\")``).\n    asyncpg requires datetime instances for ``DateTime(timezone=True)``","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py","text":"def _build_patch(\n    result: EnrichmentResult,\n    agent_provided_fields: list[str] | None = None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Translate an ``EnrichmentResult`` into the storage PATCH body.\n\n    ORM-column fields go at the top level; metadata fields land under\n    ``metadata_patch`` for the storage layer's atomic JSONB merge.\n\n    ``agent_provided_fields`` is the publisher's snapshot of which\n    columns the agent set explicitly at write time. Those fields are\n    excluded from the PATCH so a redelivery (or a slow worker run)\n    can't downgrade an agent-provided ``weight=0.9`` back to\n    ``EnrichmentResult.weight``'s default of ``0.7``. Critical because\n    Pydantic defaults survive ``exclude_none=True`` — every event\n    technically carries values for ``memory_type``, ``weight``,\n    ``status``.\n\n    ``ts_valid_*`` are emitted as ISO strings (``model_dump(mode=\"json\")``).\n    asyncpg requires datetime instances for ``DateTime(timezone=True)``\n    columns and rejects ISO strings with ``CannotCoerceError``, so the\n    storage layer's ``PATCH /memories/{id}`` route calls\n    ``_parse_datetimes(body)`` at the API boundary to coerce these\n    fields before the SQL UPDATE runs (mirrors the POST route's\n    pre-existing parse step). Keeping the worker's payload as ISO\n    strings keeps it JSON-serialisable end-to-end (httpx ``json=``\n    falls back to stdlib ``json.dumps`` which can't serialise\n    ``datetime``); the coercion lives at the storage boundary\n    rather than per-publisher. This was a real production bug\n    until 2026-04-26 — see PR <CAURA-595-ts-valid-iso-coercion>.\n    \"\"\"\n    skip = frozenset(agent_provided_fields or ())\n    dump = result.model_dump(mode=\"json\", exclude_none=True)\n\n    # ``ts_valid_*`` are semantically meaningful as ``None`` (\"this\n    # memory has no validity bounds\"), distinct from \"field absent\".\n    # ``exclude_none=True`` would silently drop them, leaving stale\n    # dates from a prior enrichment run intact in storage. Preserve\n    # them explicitly so a re-delivery (or a different LLM run that\n    # doesn't infer dates) can clear what an earlier run wrote.\n    #\n    # GUARD: only null-patch when the result came from a real LLM\n    # call (``llm_ms > 0``). The heuristic fallback (``fake_enrich``\n    # — used when the configured provider fails after retries +\n    # fallback chain exhausts) NEVER infers dates, so its absence of\n    # ``ts_valid_*`` is \"I don't know\", not \"no bounds\". Without this\n    # guard, a Pub/Sub redelivery that coincides with an LLM outage\n    # would land on the heuristic and wipe temporal bounds a prior\n    # successful run wrote — silent data loss with no log surface.\n    if result.llm_ms > 0:\n        for ts_field in (\"ts_valid_start\", \"ts_valid_end\"):\n            if ts_field not in skip and ts_field not in dump:\n                dump[ts_field] = None\n\n    patch: dict = {}\n    for field in _ENRICHMENT_ORM_FIELDS:\n        if field in skip:\n            continue\n        if field in dump:\n            value = dump[field]\n            # Empty title from the LLM (or from ``fake_enrich`` for\n            # very short content) shouldn't clobber a previously-\n            # stored valid title. Other ORM fields (``memory_type``,\n            # ``weight``, ``status``) have schema defaults that\n            # ``EnrichmentResult`` always emits — those go through\n            # ``agent_provided_fields`` for the gate. ``title`` has\n            # no agent-side counterpart (it's enricher-only output)\n            # and no useful default — empty == \"didn't infer\".\n            if field == \"title\" and value == \"\":\n                continue\n            patch[field] = value\n\n    # The hot-path writer set ``metadata.enrichment_pending=true`` when\n    # deferring; clear it unconditionally on every successful worker\n    # PATCH so a read-after-success returns clean state. Pre-seeds the\n    # patch dict so the ``if metadata_patch:`` gate below always fires\n    # (when heuristic fallback produces no real metadata fields, this\n    # seed ensures the PATCH still goes out and clears the stale flag\n    # — without it, a fallback redelivery would silently keep the row\n    # marked pending forever). Storage's JSONB ``||`` merge overwrites\n    # a prior ``True`` with ``False`` cleanly.\n    metadata_patch: dict = {\"enrichment_pending\": False}\n    for field in _ENRICHMENT_METADATA_FIELDS:\n        if field in skip:\n            continue\n        value = dump.get(field)\n        if field in _ENRICHMENT_ALWAYS_WRITE_METADATA:\n            # Same ``llm_ms > 0`` guard as ``ts_valid_*`` above:\n            # ``fake_enrich`` returns ``contains_pii=False``,\n            # ``pii_types=[]``, ``tags=[]``, ``retrieval_hint=\"\"`` as\n            # Pydantic defaults — all non-None. Without this guard, a\n            # heuristic-fallback redelivery (LLM outage during a\n            # storage 5xx retry) would clobber real LLM-produced PII\n            # detection + recall hints + tags that an earlier\n            # successful run wrote. The ``llm_ms > 0`` proxy is the\n            # same one ``ts_valid_*`` uses; ``fake_enrich`` hard-codes\n            # ``llm_ms=0`` so the proxy is reliable.\n            if result.llm_ms > 0 and value is not None:\n                metadata_patch[field] = value\n            continue\n        # Other metadata fields: drop the specific defaults that carry\n        # no information — heuristic-fallback ``\"summary\": \"\"``,\n        # ``\"llm_ms\": 0`` from early-return paths. Listed by value\n        # rather than a blanket ``if not value`` so a future\n        # ``dict``-typed field isn't accidentally silenced.\n        if value is None or value in (False, 0, \"\", []):\n            continue\n        metadata_patch[field] = value\n    if metadata_patch:\n        patch[\"metadata_patch\"] = metadata_patch\n\n    return patch\n\n\nasync def handle_enrich_request(event: Event) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Process a single enrich-request event.\n\n    Mirrors :func:`handle_embed_request`'s shape: validate → reconstruct\n    tenant config → run enricher (3-tier fallback inside\n    ``common.enrichment.enrich_memory``) → PATCH result onto the row.\n    \"\"\"\n    try:\n        request = MemoryEnrichRequest(**event.payload)\n    except ValidationError:\n        logger.exception(\n            \"dropping malformed enrich-request payload\",\n            extra={\n                \"event_type\": event.event_type,\n                \"event_id\": str(event.event_id),\n                \"dropped\": True,\n            },\n        )\n        return\n\n    if _storage_client_factory is None:\n        logger.error(\n            \"dropping enrich-request: consumer not configured\",\n            extra={\n                \"event_id\": str(event.event_id),\n                \"memory_id\": str(request.memory_id),\n                \"dropped\": True,\n            },\n        )\n        return\n\n    storage = _storage_client_factory()\n    tenant_config = _build_tenant_config(request)\n\n    reference_dt = datetime.fromisoformat(request.reference_datetime) if request.reference_datetime else None\n\n    # ``enrich_memory`` never raises — it falls through to the keyword\n    # heuristic (``fake_enrich``) on every error path. So a transient\n    # provider failure can't nack-loop the subscription.\n    result = await enrich_memory(\n        request.content,\n        tenant_config,\n        reference_datetime=reference_dt,\n    )\n\n    patch = _build_patch(result, request.agent_provided_fields)\n\n    # Surface the sync-vs-async behavioural gap: the synchronous write\n    # path in ``memory_service.py`` fans ``atomic_facts`` out into\n    # child memories. The async worker doesn't yet — content with\n    # multiple distinct claims gets fewer memories on this path.\n    # Implementing child-memory creation in the worker requires a\n    # fresh embed roundtrip per child + a parent-link plumb through\n    # storage; tracked separately.\n    #\n    # Logged at WARNING (not ERROR): the gap is real but expected\n    # under the current PR scope, and ERROR-paging on every multi-fact\n    # write would drown the on-call alert channel without giving them\n    # an actionable fix. The follow-up ticket reference makes the gap\n    # discoverable; a dashboard counter on the WARNING string lets\n    # operators quantify exposure.\n    if result.atomic_facts:\n        logger.warning(\n            \"enrich-request for memory %s produced %d atomic_facts; \"\n            \"child-memory creation not yet implemented in async path \"\n            \"(tracked: CAURA-595 follow-up) — secondary facts will \"\n            \"NOT appear as child memories\",\n            request.memory_id,\n            len(result.atomic_facts),\n        )\n\n    # Per-tenant slot scoped to the PATCH only; matches the embed\n    # consumer above. The LLM enrichment call upstream is the\n    # expensive step but doesn't touch the storage-writer pool.\n    async with per_tenant_storage_slot(request.tenant_id):\n        await update_memory_enrichment(\n            storage,\n            memory_id=request.memory_id,\n            tenant_id=request.tenant_id,\n            fields=patch,\n        )\n\n    # Back-channel: announce successful enrichment so core-api (or any\n    # other subscriber) can react. Best-effort — a publish failure\n    # MUST NOT nack the upstream PATCH that already succeeded; the\n    # enrichment is durable in storage either way. ``logger.exception``\n    # captures the failure for alerting; the consumer returns\n    # successfully so Pub/Sub acks the input event.\n    try:\n        await publish_memory_enriched(\n            memory_id=request.memory_id,\n            tenant_id=request.tenant_id,\n            content=request.content,\n            retrieval_hint=result.retrieval_hint or \"\",\n        )\n    except Exception:\n        logger.exception(\n            \"enriched back-channel publish failed; ack-continuing\",\n            extra={\n                \"memory_id\": str(request.memory_id),\n                \"tenant_id\": request.tenant_id,\n            },\n        )\n\n    logger.info(\n        \"enrich-request processed\",\n        extra={\n            \"memory_id\": str(request.memory_id),\n            \"tenant_id\": request.tenant_id,\n            \"provider\": request.enrichment_provider or \"platform\",\n            \"memory_type\": result.memory_type,\n            \"llm_ms\": result.llm_ms,\n        },\n    )\n\n\nclass _SuppressionAdapter(SuppressionStorageAdapter):\n    \"\"\"Thin adapter wiring :func:`upsert_tenant_suppression` into the\n    shared :class:`SuppressionStorageAdapter` contract (CAURA-694).\n\n    Lives in the consumer module rather than ``clients/`` so the lazy\n    storage-client lookup (``_storage_client_factory``) stays bound to\n    the consumer's ``configure`` entry point — same pattern the embed\n    + enrich handlers use to reach the storage client.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    async def set_tenant_suppression(self, *, tenant_id: str, action: str, updated_by: str | None) -> None:\n        if _storage_client_factory is None:\n            raise RuntimeError(\"consumer.configure() must run before register_consumers()\")\n        client = _storage_client_factory()\n        await upsert_tenant_suppression(\n            client,\n            tenant_id=tenant_id,\n            action=action,\n            updated_by=updated_by,\n        )\n\n\ndef register_consumers() -> None:\n    \"\"\"Wire the consumers into the event bus.\n\n    Called once at app startup, before ``bus.start()`` — the Pub/Sub\n    backend spawns its pull loops in ``start()`` based on the current\n    handler registry, so a late ``subscribe()`` would silently orphan\n    the handler.\n    \"\"\"\n    bus = get_event_bus()\n    bus.subscribe(Topics.Memory.EMBED_REQUESTED, handle_embed_request)\n    bus.subscribe(Topics.Memory.ENRICH_REQUESTED, handle_enrich_request)\n    # CAURA-694: register the org-suppression mirror handler. Subscribing\n    # here keeps the registration order single-file rather than scattered\n    # across multiple ``register_*`` entry points.\n    register_suppression_consumer(_SuppressionAdapter())","lineStart":359,"lineEnd":625,"totalLines":625,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py","time":{"start":1780728111493,"end":1780728111497}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b889e1f3f36b228016a23c12f62988191918c30def64fbcee"}},"id":"prt_e9baaa15a0019tUEJgOhqcfxw8","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","messageID":"msg_e9baa6841001Ctocor307bFP0E"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728111513,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_e97TWmVsv3ovoT8Ib2k66SLW","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py","offset":120,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n120:         # or test inspector that snapshots the call args would\n121:         # otherwise see the rotated token retro-fitted into the first\n122:         # call's record).\n123:         headers = {**headers, **await fetch_auth_header(_audience)}\n124:         resp = await fn(*args, headers=headers, **kwargs)\n125:     return resp\n126: \n127: \n128: async def find_embedding_by_content_hash(\n129:     client: httpx.AsyncClient,\n130:     *,\n131:     tenant_id: str,\n132:     content_hash: str,\n133: ) -> list[float] | None:\n134:     \"\"\"Look up a previously computed embedding for the same content.\n135: \n136:     Returns ``None`` when there's no cached row, the row exists but its\n137:     embedding is NULL (still pending), or the storage call fails for\n138:     any reason. Callers fall through to the embedding provider.\n139: \n140:     Storage contract (``GET /memories/embedding-by-content-hash``)\n141:     returns the bare ``list[float] | None`` — JSON ``null`` on miss,\n142:     not ``{\"embedding\": null}``. Treating the body as a dict and\n143:     calling ``.get(\"embedding\")`` on a JSON-null parse crashes with\n144:     ``AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'get'``,\n145:     which used to be masked by 403s before the CAURA-595 ID-token\n146:     PR landed and the cache lookup actually started succeeding.\n147:     \"\"\"\n148:     try:\n149:         resp = await _signed_call(\n150:             client.get,\n151:             f\"{_PREFIX}/memories/embedding-by-content-hash\",\n152:             params={\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, \"content_hash\": content_hash},\n153:         )\n154:         if resp.status_code != 200:\n155:             return None\n156:         # ``resp.json()`` raises on malformed bodies (a partial response\n157:         # from a stray proxy, an HTML error page sneaking through with\n158:         # a 200, etc.). The docstring promises \"fails for any reason →\n159:         # None\" so the worker falls through to a fresh provider call\n160:         # instead of nacking and forcing Pub/Sub redelivery — staying\n161:         # consistent with the ``HTTPError`` handling above.\n162:         return resp.json()\n163:     except (httpx.HTTPError, ValueError):\n164:         logger.exception(\"storage embedding-cache lookup failed; treating as miss\")\n165:         return None\n166: \n167: \n168: async def update_memory_embedding(\n169:     client: httpx.AsyncClient,\n170:     *,\n171:     memory_id: UUID,\n172:     tenant_id: str,\n173:     embedding: list[float],\n174: ) -> None:\n175:     \"\"\"PATCH the embedding onto the memory row.\n176: \n177:     Raises on transient (5xx / 429) responses so the consumer nacks\n178:     → Pub/Sub redelivers. Permanent 4xx errors (404, 422) are logged\n179:     and ack-dropped — retrying them just burns the\n180:     max-delivery-attempts budget against an event that will never\n181:     succeed (row deleted between event publish and processing, or a\n182:     schema mismatch the storage layer rejects either way).\n183: \n184:     ``tenant_id`` is included in the body so the storage layer can\n185:     guard against cross-tenant updates.\n186: \n187:     The hot-path writer set ``metadata.embedding_pending=true`` when\n188:     deferring the embed; clear it via ``metadata_patch`` on the same\n189:     PATCH so a read-after-success returns clean state instead of\n190:     confusingly claiming the row is still pending.\n191:     \"\"\"\n192:     resp = await _signed_call(\n193:         client.patch,\n194:         f\"{_PREFIX}/memories/{memory_id}\",\n195:         json={\n196:             \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n197:             \"embedding\": embedding,\n198:             \"metadata_patch\": {\"embedding_pending\": False},\n199:         },\n200:     )\n201:     if resp.status_code == 404:\n202:         # Row was deleted after the event was published — common-enough\n203:         # legitimate race that it shouldn't churn the DLQ.\n204:         logger.warning(\n205:             \"memory %s not found in storage; ack-dropping embed-request \"\n206:             \"(row deleted between publish and processing)\",\n207:             memory_id,\n208:         )\n209:         return\n210:     if resp.status_code == 422:\n211:         # Storage rejected the payload shape. Won't pass on a redelivery\n212:         # either — log loudly so the schema mismatch is visible and ack.\n213:         logger.warning(\n214:             \"storage rejected embedding PATCH for memory %s with 422; ack-dropping\",\n215:             memory_id,\n216:         )\n217:         return\n218:     # 5xx / 429 / network → raise → consumer nacks → Pub/Sub redelivers.\n219:     resp.raise_for_status()\n220: \n221: \n222: @dataclass(frozen=True)\n223: class NullEmbeddingRow:\n224:     \"\"\"Identifiers for one memory row that needs re-embedding.\n225: \n226:     Carries only the fields needed to address a follow-up\n227:     ``GET /memories/{id}`` fetch. Raw ``content`` / ``content_hash``\n228:     are NOT included — the listing endpoint deliberately returns\n229:     ids-only (defence-in-depth on the unauthenticated storage API),\n230:     and the worker fetches content per row before publishing.\n231:     \"\"\"\n232: \n233:     memory_id: UUID\n234:     tenant_id: str\n235: \n236: \n237: async def iter_memories_with_null_embedding(\n238:     client: httpx.AsyncClient,\n239:     *,\n\n(Showing lines 120-239 of 502. Use offset=240 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"        # or test inspector that snapshots the call args would\n        # otherwise see the rotated token retro-fitted into the first\n        # call's record).\n        headers = {**headers, **await fetch_auth_header(_audience)}\n        resp = await fn(*args, headers=headers, **kwargs)\n    return resp\n\n\nasync def find_embedding_by_content_hash(\n    client: httpx.AsyncClient,\n    *,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    content_hash: str,\n) -> list[float] | None:\n    \"\"\"Look up a previously computed embedding for the same content.\n\n    Returns ``None`` when there's no cached row, the row exists but its\n    embedding is NULL (still pending), or the storage call fails for\n    any reason. Callers fall through to the embedding provider.\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py","text":"        # or test inspector that snapshots the call args would\n        # otherwise see the rotated token retro-fitted into the first\n        # call's record).\n        headers = {**headers, **await fetch_auth_header(_audience)}\n        resp = await fn(*args, headers=headers, **kwargs)\n    return resp\n\n\nasync def find_embedding_by_content_hash(\n    client: httpx.AsyncClient,\n    *,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    content_hash: str,\n) -> list[float] | None:\n    \"\"\"Look up a previously computed embedding for the same content.\n\n    Returns ``None`` when there's no cached row, the row exists but its\n    embedding is NULL (still pending), or the storage call fails for\n    any reason. Callers fall through to the embedding provider.\n\n    Storage contract (``GET /memories/embedding-by-content-hash``)\n    returns the bare ``list[float] | None`` — JSON ``null`` on miss,\n    not ``{\"embedding\": null}``. Treating the body as a dict and\n    calling ``.get(\"embedding\")`` on a JSON-null parse crashes with\n    ``AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'get'``,\n    which used to be masked by 403s before the CAURA-595 ID-token\n    PR landed and the cache lookup actually started succeeding.\n    \"\"\"\n    try:\n        resp = await _signed_call(\n            client.get,\n            f\"{_PREFIX}/memories/embedding-by-content-hash\",\n            params={\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, \"content_hash\": content_hash},\n        )\n        if resp.status_code != 200:\n            return None\n        # ``resp.json()`` raises on malformed bodies (a partial response\n        # from a stray proxy, an HTML error page sneaking through with\n        # a 200, etc.). The docstring promises \"fails for any reason →\n        # None\" so the worker falls through to a fresh provider call\n        # instead of nacking and forcing Pub/Sub redelivery — staying\n        # consistent with the ``HTTPError`` handling above.\n        return resp.json()\n    except (httpx.HTTPError, ValueError):\n        logger.exception(\"storage embedding-cache lookup failed; treating as miss\")\n        return None\n\n\nasync def update_memory_embedding(\n    client: httpx.AsyncClient,\n    *,\n    memory_id: UUID,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    embedding: list[float],\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"PATCH the embedding onto the memory row.\n\n    Raises on transient (5xx / 429) responses so the consumer nacks\n    → Pub/Sub redelivers. Permanent 4xx errors (404, 422) are logged\n    and ack-dropped — retrying them just burns the\n    max-delivery-attempts budget against an event that will never\n    succeed (row deleted between event publish and processing, or a\n    schema mismatch the storage layer rejects either way).\n\n    ``tenant_id`` is included in the body so the storage layer can\n    guard against cross-tenant updates.\n\n    The hot-path writer set ``metadata.embedding_pending=true`` when\n    deferring the embed; clear it via ``metadata_patch`` on the same\n    PATCH so a read-after-success returns clean state instead of\n    confusingly claiming the row is still pending.\n    \"\"\"\n    resp = await _signed_call(\n        client.patch,\n        f\"{_PREFIX}/memories/{memory_id}\",\n        json={\n            \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n            \"embedding\": embedding,\n            \"metadata_patch\": {\"embedding_pending\": False},\n        },\n    )\n    if resp.status_code == 404:\n        # Row was deleted after the event was published — common-enough\n        # legitimate race that it shouldn't churn the DLQ.\n        logger.warning(\n            \"memory %s not found in storage; ack-dropping embed-request \"\n            \"(row deleted between publish and processing)\",\n            memory_id,\n        )\n        return\n    if resp.status_code == 422:\n        # Storage rejected the payload shape. Won't pass on a redelivery\n        # either — log loudly so the schema mismatch is visible and ack.\n        logger.warning(\n            \"storage rejected embedding PATCH for memory %s with 422; ack-dropping\",\n            memory_id,\n        )\n        return\n    # 5xx / 429 / network → raise → consumer nacks → Pub/Sub redelivers.\n    resp.raise_for_status()\n\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass NullEmbeddingRow:\n    \"\"\"Identifiers for one memory row that needs re-embedding.\n\n    Carries only the fields needed to address a follow-up\n    ``GET /memories/{id}`` fetch. Raw ``content`` / ``content_hash``\n    are NOT included — the listing endpoint deliberately returns\n    ids-only (defence-in-depth on the unauthenticated storage API),\n    and the worker fetches content per row before publishing.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    memory_id: UUID\n    tenant_id: str\n\n\nasync def iter_memories_with_null_embedding(\n    client: httpx.AsyncClient,\n    *,","lineStart":120,"lineEnd":239,"totalLines":502,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py","time":{"start":1780728111504,"end":1780728111512}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b889e1f3f36b228016a23c12f65748191837b67e1a632f361"}},"id":"prt_e9baaa188001yPq7YM76mQZs99","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","messageID":"msg_e9baa6841001Ctocor307bFP0E"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728111515,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_k7yp8NMUabJ7c8wbQp4zCze8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py","offset":454,"limit":110},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n454: async def update_memory_enrichment(\n455:     client: httpx.AsyncClient,\n456:     *,\n457:     memory_id: UUID,\n458:     tenant_id: str,\n459:     fields: dict,\n460: ) -> None:\n461:     \"\"\"PATCH enrichment-output fields onto the memory row.\n462: \n463:     Mirrors :func:`update_memory_embedding` for the\n464:     ``Topics.Memory.ENRICH_REQUESTED`` worker path. ``fields`` is the\n465:     pre-validated dict of column→value pairs the consumer wants to write\n466:     (memory_type, weight, title, summary, tags, status, ts_valid_*,\n467:     contains_pii, pii_types, retrieval_hint). The storage-side\n468:     ``memory_update`` filters by ``hasattr(Memory, key)`` so unknown keys\n469:     are silently dropped — caller still validates upstream against\n470:     ``EnrichmentResult`` so a typo surfaces as a Pydantic error, not a\n471:     silent no-op.\n472: \n473:     Idempotency: at-least-once delivery means a redelivered enrich event\n474:     re-PATCHes with the (deterministic up to LLM noise) same fields.\n475:     Safe — the storage update is a write-after-write.\n476: \n477:     Same 404/422 short-circuits as :func:`update_memory_embedding`.\n478:     \"\"\"\n479:     if not fields:\n480:         # Defensive — heuristic fallback may produce an all-defaults\n481:         # result; an empty PATCH is wasted work and noisy in storage logs.\n482:         logger.debug(\"skipping empty enrichment PATCH for memory %s\", memory_id)\n483:         return\n484:     resp = await _signed_call(\n485:         client.patch,\n486:         f\"{_PREFIX}/memories/{memory_id}\",\n487:         json={\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, **fields},\n488:     )\n489:     if resp.status_code == 404:\n490:         logger.warning(\n491:             \"memory %s not found in storage; ack-dropping enrich-request \"\n492:             \"(row deleted between publish and processing)\",\n493:             memory_id,\n494:         )\n495:         return\n496:     if resp.status_code == 422:\n497:         logger.warning(\n498:             \"storage rejected enrichment PATCH for memory %s with 422; ack-dropping\",\n499:             memory_id,\n500:         )\n501:         return\n502:     resp.raise_for_status()\n\n(End of file - total 502 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"async def update_memory_enrichment(\n    client: httpx.AsyncClient,\n    *,\n    memory_id: UUID,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    fields: dict,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"PATCH enrichment-output fields onto the memory row.\n\n    Mirrors :func:`update_memory_embedding` for the\n    ``Topics.Memory.ENRICH_REQUESTED`` worker path. ``fields`` is the\n    pre-validated dict of column→value pairs the consumer wants to write\n    (memory_type, weight, title, summary, tags, status, ts_valid_*,\n    contains_pii, pii_types, retrieval_hint). The storage-side\n    ``memory_update`` filters by ``hasattr(Memory, key)`` so unknown keys\n    are silently dropped — caller still validates upstream against\n    ``EnrichmentResult`` so a typo surfaces as a Pydantic error, not a\n    silent no-op.\n\n    Idempotency: at-least-once delivery means a redelivered enrich event","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py","text":"async def update_memory_enrichment(\n    client: httpx.AsyncClient,\n    *,\n    memory_id: UUID,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    fields: dict,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"PATCH enrichment-output fields onto the memory row.\n\n    Mirrors :func:`update_memory_embedding` for the\n    ``Topics.Memory.ENRICH_REQUESTED`` worker path. ``fields`` is the\n    pre-validated dict of column→value pairs the consumer wants to write\n    (memory_type, weight, title, summary, tags, status, ts_valid_*,\n    contains_pii, pii_types, retrieval_hint). The storage-side\n    ``memory_update`` filters by ``hasattr(Memory, key)`` so unknown keys\n    are silently dropped — caller still validates upstream against\n    ``EnrichmentResult`` so a typo surfaces as a Pydantic error, not a\n    silent no-op.\n\n    Idempotency: at-least-once delivery means a redelivered enrich event\n    re-PATCHes with the (deterministic up to LLM noise) same fields.\n    Safe — the storage update is a write-after-write.\n\n    Same 404/422 short-circuits as :func:`update_memory_embedding`.\n    \"\"\"\n    if not fields:\n        # Defensive — heuristic fallback may produce an all-defaults\n        # result; an empty PATCH is wasted work and noisy in storage logs.\n        logger.debug(\"skipping empty enrichment PATCH for memory %s\", memory_id)\n        return\n    resp = await _signed_call(\n        client.patch,\n        f\"{_PREFIX}/memories/{memory_id}\",\n        json={\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, **fields},\n    )\n    if resp.status_code == 404:\n        logger.warning(\n            \"memory %s not found in storage; ack-dropping enrich-request \"\n            \"(row deleted between publish and processing)\",\n            memory_id,\n        )\n        return\n    if resp.status_code == 422:\n        logger.warning(\n            \"storage rejected enrichment PATCH for memory %s with 422; ack-dropping\",\n            memory_id,\n        )\n        return\n    resp.raise_for_status()","lineStart":454,"lineEnd":502,"totalLines":502,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py","time":{"start":1780728111507,"end":1780728111515}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b889e1f3f36b228016a23c12f6580819183f11dd5fbd3955f"}},"id":"prt_e9baaa19000110xHrnu9tE5Fem","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","messageID":"msg_e9baa6841001Ctocor307bFP0E"}}
