{"type":"text","timestamp":1780728145224,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"id":"prt_e9bab0739001Sleksb2gUY4C50","messageID":"msg_e9baaf730001FJHQVBg5JR83Sk","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","type":"text","text":"MemClaw does have a separate ingest chunker for large content, so I’m checking that limited path to distinguish real chunking from atomic-fact fan-out.","time":{"start":1780728137529,"end":1780728145223},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0664681595a21984016a23c14981748191a0a37f484aab4382","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728145281,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_xSrqzwgi2825Y1B7TMLItomP","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/constants.py","offset":1,"limit":20},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/constants.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"DB-query constants shared between core-api and core-storage-api.\"\"\"\n2: \n3: # ── Embeddings ──\n4: # Native dim of the default embedder (BAAI/bge-m3, see local-embedder docs).\n5: # Schema upgrade lives in alembic migration 012_vector_dim_1024.py — keep\n6: # this constant in lock-step with that migration.\n7: VECTOR_DIM = 1024\n8: \n9: # ── Write-time semantic dedup ──\n10: SEMANTIC_DEDUP_THRESHOLD = 0.95  # cosine similarity above this -> near-duplicate\n11: SEMANTIC_DEDUP_CANDIDATE_LIMIT = 1  # only need to know if any match exists\n12: \n13: # Two-tier dedup constants (A1 #15). The dispatch that consumes them\n14: # lives in A1 #16. Today's single-tier code keeps using\n15: # ``SEMANTIC_DEDUP_THRESHOLD`` above — this PR adds the band cutoffs\n16: # without changing any call site.\n17: #\n18: # Decision band (cosine similarity to nearest existing memory):\n19: #   ≥ AUTO          → auto-reject (clear duplicate; no LLM)\n20: #   JUDGE ≤ s < AUTO → LLM judge decides (A1 #16; A4 #12 verdict+confidence)\n\n(Showing lines 1-20 of 388. Use offset=21 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"DB-query constants shared between core-api and core-storage-api.\"\"\"\n\n# ── Embeddings ──\n# Native dim of the default embedder (BAAI/bge-m3, see local-embedder docs).\n# Schema upgrade lives in alembic migration 012_vector_dim_1024.py — keep\n# this constant in lock-step with that migration.\nVECTOR_DIM = 1024\n\n# ── Write-time semantic dedup ──\nSEMANTIC_DEDUP_THRESHOLD = 0.95  # cosine similarity above this -> near-duplicate\nSEMANTIC_DEDUP_CANDIDATE_LIMIT = 1  # only need to know if any match exists\n\n# Two-tier dedup constants (A1 #15). The dispatch that consumes them\n# lives in A1 #16. Today's single-tier code keeps using\n# ``SEMANTIC_DEDUP_THRESHOLD`` above — this PR adds the band cutoffs\n# without changing any call site.\n#\n# Decision band (cosine similarity to nearest existing memory):\n#   ≥ AUTO          → auto-reject (clear duplicate; no LLM)\n#   JUDGE ≤ s < AUTO → LLM judge decides (A1 #16; A4 #12 verdict+confidence)","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/constants.py","text":"\"\"\"DB-query constants shared between core-api and core-storage-api.\"\"\"\n\n# ── Embeddings ──\n# Native dim of the default embedder (BAAI/bge-m3, see local-embedder docs).\n# Schema upgrade lives in alembic migration 012_vector_dim_1024.py — keep\n# this constant in lock-step with that migration.\nVECTOR_DIM = 1024\n\n# ── Write-time semantic dedup ──\nSEMANTIC_DEDUP_THRESHOLD = 0.95  # cosine similarity above this -> near-duplicate\nSEMANTIC_DEDUP_CANDIDATE_LIMIT = 1  # only need to know if any match exists\n\n# Two-tier dedup constants (A1 #15). The dispatch that consumes them\n# lives in A1 #16. Today's single-tier code keeps using\n# ``SEMANTIC_DEDUP_THRESHOLD`` above — this PR adds the band cutoffs\n# without changing any call site.\n#\n# Decision band (cosine similarity to nearest existing memory):\n#   ≥ AUTO          → auto-reject (clear duplicate; no LLM)\n#   JUDGE ≤ s < AUTO → LLM judge decides (A1 #16; A4 #12 verdict+confidence)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":20,"totalLines":388,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/constants.py","time":{"start":1780728145266,"end":1780728145275}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0664681595a21984016a23c1512ee481918407d862d2faf92c"}},"id":"prt_e9bab2571001haug26N8qWBZLR","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","messageID":"msg_e9baaf730001FJHQVBg5JR83Sk"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728145282,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_tscxhMtNrGmadpTAuhfT5zAE","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/providers/local.py","offset":1,"limit":90},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/providers/local.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Local embedding provider using sentence-transformers.\n2: \n3: Runs a local model (default: BAAI/bge-base-en-v1.5) for embedding generation.\n4: The sentence-transformers package is lazy-imported so it remains an optional\n5: dependency.\n6: \"\"\"\n7: \n8: from __future__ import annotations\n9: \n10: import asyncio\n11: import logging\n12: \n13: from common.constants import VECTOR_DIM\n14: \n15: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n16: \n17: \n18: class LocalEmbedding:\n19:     \"\"\"Embedding provider backed by a local sentence-transformers model.\"\"\"\n20: \n21:     def __init__(self, model_name: str = \"BAAI/bge-base-en-v1.5\") -> None:\n22:         self._model_name = model_name\n23:         self._model = None\n24:         self._load_lock = asyncio.Lock()\n25: \n26:     @property\n27:     def provider_name(self) -> str:\n28:         return \"local\"\n29: \n30:     @property\n31:     def model(self) -> str:\n32:         return self._model_name\n33: \n34:     # ------------------------------------------------------------------\n35:     # Internal helpers\n36:     # ------------------------------------------------------------------\n37: \n38:     async def _ensure_model(self) -> None:\n39:         if self._model is not None:\n40:             return\n41:         async with self._load_lock:\n42:             if self._model is not None:\n43:                 return\n44:             try:\n45:                 from sentence_transformers import SentenceTransformer\n46:             except ImportError:\n47:                 raise ImportError(\n48:                     \"sentence-transformers is required for local embeddings. \"\n49:                     \"Install it with: pip install sentence-transformers\"\n50:                 ) from None\n51:             logger.info(\"Loading local embedding model: %s\", self._model_name)\n52:             loop = asyncio.get_running_loop()\n53:             model = await loop.run_in_executor(\n54:                 None, lambda: SentenceTransformer(self._model_name)\n55:             )\n56:             test_dim = model.get_sentence_embedding_dimension()\n57:             if test_dim != VECTOR_DIM:\n58:                 logger.warning(\n59:                     \"Model %s produces %d-dim vectors, expected %d (VECTOR_DIM)\",\n60:                     self._model_name,\n61:                     test_dim,\n62:                     VECTOR_DIM,\n63:                 )\n64:             self._model = model\n65: \n66:     # ------------------------------------------------------------------\n67:     # Public API\n68:     # ------------------------------------------------------------------\n69: \n70:     async def embed(self, text: str) -> list[float]:\n71:         \"\"\"Embed a single text string.\"\"\"\n72:         await self._ensure_model()\n73:         loop = asyncio.get_running_loop()\n74:         vec = await loop.run_in_executor(\n75:             None,\n76:             lambda: self._model.encode(text, normalize_embeddings=True),\n77:         )\n78:         return vec.tolist()\n79: \n80:     async def embed_batch(self, texts: list[str]) -> list[list[float]]:\n81:         \"\"\"Embed a batch of texts.\"\"\"\n82:         await self._ensure_model()\n83:         loop = asyncio.get_running_loop()\n84:         vecs = await loop.run_in_executor(\n85:             None,\n86:             lambda: self._model.encode(texts, normalize_embeddings=True, batch_size=32),\n87:         )\n88:         return vecs.tolist()\n89: \n90:     # Deliberately does NOT implement ``embed_query`` — sentence-\n\n(Showing lines 1-90 of 95. Use offset=91 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Local embedding provider using sentence-transformers.\n\nRuns a local model (default: BAAI/bge-base-en-v1.5) for embedding generation.\nThe sentence-transformers package is lazy-imported so it remains an optional\ndependency.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport asyncio\nimport logging\n\nfrom common.constants import VECTOR_DIM\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n\nclass LocalEmbedding:\n    \"\"\"Embedding provider backed by a local sentence-transformers model.\"\"\"\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/providers/local.py","text":"\"\"\"Local embedding provider using sentence-transformers.\n\nRuns a local model (default: BAAI/bge-base-en-v1.5) for embedding generation.\nThe sentence-transformers package is lazy-imported so it remains an optional\ndependency.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport asyncio\nimport logging\n\nfrom common.constants import VECTOR_DIM\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n\nclass LocalEmbedding:\n    \"\"\"Embedding provider backed by a local sentence-transformers model.\"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self, model_name: str = \"BAAI/bge-base-en-v1.5\") -> None:\n        self._model_name = model_name\n        self._model = None\n        self._load_lock = asyncio.Lock()\n\n    @property\n    def provider_name(self) -> str:\n        return \"local\"\n\n    @property\n    def model(self) -> str:\n        return self._model_name\n\n    # ------------------------------------------------------------------\n    # Internal helpers\n    # ------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n    async def _ensure_model(self) -> None:\n        if self._model is not None:\n            return\n        async with self._load_lock:\n            if self._model is not None:\n                return\n            try:\n                from sentence_transformers import SentenceTransformer\n            except ImportError:\n                raise ImportError(\n                    \"sentence-transformers is required for local embeddings. \"\n                    \"Install it with: pip install sentence-transformers\"\n                ) from None\n            logger.info(\"Loading local embedding model: %s\", self._model_name)\n            loop = asyncio.get_running_loop()\n            model = await loop.run_in_executor(\n                None, lambda: SentenceTransformer(self._model_name)\n            )\n            test_dim = model.get_sentence_embedding_dimension()\n            if test_dim != VECTOR_DIM:\n                logger.warning(\n                    \"Model %s produces %d-dim vectors, expected %d (VECTOR_DIM)\",\n                    self._model_name,\n                    test_dim,\n                    VECTOR_DIM,\n                )\n            self._model = model\n\n    # ------------------------------------------------------------------\n    # Public API\n    # ------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n    async def embed(self, text: str) -> list[float]:\n        \"\"\"Embed a single text string.\"\"\"\n        await self._ensure_model()\n        loop = asyncio.get_running_loop()\n        vec = await loop.run_in_executor(\n            None,\n            lambda: self._model.encode(text, normalize_embeddings=True),\n        )\n        return vec.tolist()\n\n    async def embed_batch(self, texts: list[str]) -> list[list[float]]:\n        \"\"\"Embed a batch of texts.\"\"\"\n        await self._ensure_model()\n        loop = asyncio.get_running_loop()\n        vecs = await loop.run_in_executor(\n            None,\n            lambda: self._model.encode(texts, normalize_embeddings=True, batch_size=32),\n        )\n        return vecs.tolist()\n\n    # Deliberately does NOT implement ``embed_query`` — sentence-","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":90,"totalLines":95,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/providers/local.py","time":{"start":1780728145268,"end":1780728145278}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0664681595a21984016a23c1512eec819180de56abc331358b"}},"id":"prt_e9bab2573001ZfGpswVYoVD0Re","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","messageID":"msg_e9baaf730001FJHQVBg5JR83Sk"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728145282,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_4TQHKhEqPSeMvv9k9ksJcy8q","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/providers/openai.py","offset":120,"limit":70},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/providers/openai.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n120:             # Undersized passthrough is silently broken: returning a\n121:             # vector with fewer than ``truncate_to_dim`` elements would\n122:             # produce inserts that pgvector rejects with\n123:             # ``expected N dimensions, not M``. Fail fast here so the\n124:             # mismatch is attributable to the model+truncate config,\n125:             # not surfaced obliquely as a write error far downstream.\n126:             raise ValueError(\n127:                 f\"Model returned {len(emb)}-dim vector but truncate_to_dim=\"\n128:                 f\"{self._truncate_to_dim}; the configured model must produce \"\n129:                 f\"at least {self._truncate_to_dim} native dimensions.\"\n130:             )\n131:         return emb\n132: \n133:     async def embed(self, text: str) -> list[float]:\n134:         \"\"\"Generate an embedding vector for a single text (document/ingest path).\"\"\"\n135:         kwargs: dict = {\"model\": self._model, \"input\": text}\n136:         if self._send_dimensions:\n137:             kwargs[\"dimensions\"] = VECTOR_DIM\n138:         response = await self._client.embeddings.create(**kwargs)\n139:         return self._postprocess(response.data[0].embedding)\n140: \n141:     async def embed_batch(self, texts: list[str]) -> list[list[float]]:\n142:         \"\"\"Generate embedding vectors for multiple texts in one call.\"\"\"\n143:         kwargs: dict = {\"model\": self._model, \"input\": texts}\n144:         if self._send_dimensions:\n145:             kwargs[\"dimensions\"] = VECTOR_DIM\n146:         response = await self._client.embeddings.create(**kwargs)\n147:         # OpenAI returns embeddings sorted by index\n148:         sorted_data = sorted(response.data, key=lambda x: x.index)\n149:         return [self._postprocess(item.embedding) for item in sorted_data]\n150: \n151:     async def embed_query(\n152:         self, text: str, instruction: str | None = None\n153:     ) -> list[float]:\n154:         \"\"\"Generate an embedding vector for a search-side query.\n155: \n156:         For instruction-aware models (Qwen3-Embedding, e5-instruct), prepends\n157:         the resolved instruction in the convention these models were trained\n158:         with: ``\"Instruct: <task>\\\\nQuery: <text>\"``. The instruction is\n159:         resolved as: per-call *instruction* arg → constructor\n160:         *query_instruction* → no prefix.\n161: \n162:         For symmetric models (bge-m3, snowflake-arctic-l, gte-en-v1.5,\n163:         OpenAI text-embedding-3-small), pass no instruction at construction\n164:         time and this is equivalent to :meth:`embed`.\n165:         \"\"\"\n166:         instr = instruction or self._query_instruction\n167:         if instr:\n168:             text = f\"Instruct: {instr}\\nQuery: {text}\"\n169:         return await self.embed(text)\n\n(End of file - total 169 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"            # Undersized passthrough is silently broken: returning a\n            # vector with fewer than ``truncate_to_dim`` elements would\n            # produce inserts that pgvector rejects with\n            # ``expected N dimensions, not M``. Fail fast here so the\n            # mismatch is attributable to the model+truncate config,\n            # not surfaced obliquely as a write error far downstream.\n            raise ValueError(\n                f\"Model returned {len(emb)}-dim vector but truncate_to_dim=\"\n                f\"{self._truncate_to_dim}; the configured model must produce \"\n                f\"at least {self._truncate_to_dim} native dimensions.\"\n            )\n        return emb\n\n    async def embed(self, text: str) -> list[float]:\n        \"\"\"Generate an embedding vector for a single text (document/ingest path).\"\"\"\n        kwargs: dict = {\"model\": self._model, \"input\": text}\n        if self._send_dimensions:\n            kwargs[\"dimensions\"] = VECTOR_DIM\n        response = await self._client.embeddings.create(**kwargs)\n        return self._postprocess(response.data[0].embedding)","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/providers/openai.py","text":"            # Undersized passthrough is silently broken: returning a\n            # vector with fewer than ``truncate_to_dim`` elements would\n            # produce inserts that pgvector rejects with\n            # ``expected N dimensions, not M``. Fail fast here so the\n            # mismatch is attributable to the model+truncate config,\n            # not surfaced obliquely as a write error far downstream.\n            raise ValueError(\n                f\"Model returned {len(emb)}-dim vector but truncate_to_dim=\"\n                f\"{self._truncate_to_dim}; the configured model must produce \"\n                f\"at least {self._truncate_to_dim} native dimensions.\"\n            )\n        return emb\n\n    async def embed(self, text: str) -> list[float]:\n        \"\"\"Generate an embedding vector for a single text (document/ingest path).\"\"\"\n        kwargs: dict = {\"model\": self._model, \"input\": text}\n        if self._send_dimensions:\n            kwargs[\"dimensions\"] = VECTOR_DIM\n        response = await self._client.embeddings.create(**kwargs)\n        return self._postprocess(response.data[0].embedding)\n\n    async def embed_batch(self, texts: list[str]) -> list[list[float]]:\n        \"\"\"Generate embedding vectors for multiple texts in one call.\"\"\"\n        kwargs: dict = {\"model\": self._model, \"input\": texts}\n        if self._send_dimensions:\n            kwargs[\"dimensions\"] = VECTOR_DIM\n        response = await self._client.embeddings.create(**kwargs)\n        # OpenAI returns embeddings sorted by index\n        sorted_data = sorted(response.data, key=lambda x: x.index)\n        return [self._postprocess(item.embedding) for item in sorted_data]\n\n    async def embed_query(\n        self, text: str, instruction: str | None = None\n    ) -> list[float]:\n        \"\"\"Generate an embedding vector for a search-side query.\n\n        For instruction-aware models (Qwen3-Embedding, e5-instruct), prepends\n        the resolved instruction in the convention these models were trained\n        with: ``\"Instruct: <task>\\\\nQuery: <text>\"``. The instruction is\n        resolved as: per-call *instruction* arg → constructor\n        *query_instruction* → no prefix.\n\n        For symmetric models (bge-m3, snowflake-arctic-l, gte-en-v1.5,\n        OpenAI text-embedding-3-small), pass no instruction at construction\n        time and this is equivalent to :meth:`embed`.\n        \"\"\"\n        instr = instruction or self._query_instruction\n        if instr:\n            text = f\"Instruct: {instr}\\nQuery: {text}\"\n        return await self.embed(text)","lineStart":120,"lineEnd":169,"totalLines":169,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/embedding/providers/openai.py","time":{"start":1780728145270,"end":1780728145279}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0664681595a21984016a23c1512ef08191921c5055c97a79a5"}},"id":"prt_e9bab2574001EosP1UZCEhMRYN","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","messageID":"msg_e9baaf730001FJHQVBg5JR83Sk"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728145282,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_yVu9KvSrqsA6wPQ2CHrUgkWC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py","offset":335,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n335: def chunk_blocks(\n336:     blocks: list[Block],\n337:     *,\n338:     soft_tokens: int = SECTION_SOFT_TOKENS,\n339:     hard_tokens: int = SECTION_HARD_TOKENS,\n340: ) -> list[Section]:\n341:     \"\"\"Greedy-pack typed blocks into Sections under token caps.\n342: \n343:     Section boundary triggers (in priority order):\n344:       1. A heading at depth ≤ 2 (H1/H2) AND the current accumulator is non-empty.\n345:          → close current section, start a new one with this heading.\n346:       2. Adding the next block would exceed ``soft_tokens``.\n347:          → close current section, the next block starts a new one.\n348: \n349:     Lists, tables, and code blocks are never split mid-element. If a\n350:     single such block exceeds ``hard_tokens`` on its own, it stands as\n351:     its own oversized section (the LLM handles oversized inputs better\n352:     than malformed half-tables).\n353: \n354:     Paragraphs that exceed ``hard_tokens`` alone get sentence-split via\n355:     pysbd into multiple sub-paragraphs, each its own paragraph block in\n356:     a new section.\n357: \n358:     The breadcrumb on each emitted Section reflects the most recent H1\n359:     and H2 (and H3 if shallow enough) encountered before that section.\n360:     Without headings (plain-text input), breadcrumb is \"\".\n361:     \"\"\"\n362:     sections: list[Section] = []\n363:     current_text_parts: list[str] = []\n364:     current_tokens = 0\n365:     current_types: list[BlockType] = []\n366:     # Breadcrumb tracking: stack of (depth, text) for the current heading trail\n367:     breadcrumb_stack: list[tuple[int, str]] = []\n368: \n369:     def _current_breadcrumb() -> str:\n370:         return \" > \".join(text for _, text in breadcrumb_stack)\n371: \n372:     def _flush() -> None:\n373:         nonlocal current_text_parts, current_tokens, current_types\n374:         if not current_text_parts:\n375:             return\n376:         joined = \"\\n\\n\".join(current_text_parts).strip()\n377:         if joined:\n378:             sections.append(\n379:                 Section(\n380:                     text=joined,\n381:                     breadcrumb=_current_breadcrumb(),\n382:                     token_count=current_tokens,\n383:                     block_types=list(current_types),\n384:                 )\n385:             )\n386:         current_text_parts = []\n387:         current_tokens = 0\n388:         current_types = []\n389: \n390:     for block in blocks:\n391:         block_tokens = _count_tokens(block.text)\n392: \n393:         if block.type == \"heading\":\n394:             # An H1/H2 closes the current section if non-empty. Flush\n395:             # BEFORE updating the heading stack so the prior section's\n396:             # breadcrumb reflects the OLD heading trail (the new heading\n397:             # belongs to the next section, not the one we're closing).\n398:             if block.depth <= 2 and current_text_parts:\n399:                 _flush()\n400:             # Update breadcrumb stack: pop deeper-or-equal entries, push this one.\n401:             while breadcrumb_stack and breadcrumb_stack[-1][0] >= block.depth:\n402:                 breadcrumb_stack.pop()\n403:             breadcrumb_stack.append((block.depth, block.text))\n404:             # The heading text itself goes into the next section as a\n405:             # rendered line (LLM benefits from seeing the heading).\n406:             current_text_parts.append((\"#\" * block.depth) + \" \" + block.text)\n407:             current_tokens += block_tokens\n408:             current_types.append(block.type)\n409:             continue\n410: \n411:         # Oversized atomic blocks (list/table/code) — emit as own section\n412:         # without splitting.\n413:         if block.type in (\"list\", \"table\", \"code\") and block_tokens > hard_tokens:\n414:             _flush()\n415:             sections.append(\n416:                 Section(\n417:                     text=block.text,\n418:                     breadcrumb=_current_breadcrumb(),\n419:                     token_count=block_tokens,\n420:                     block_types=[block.type],\n421:                 )\n422:             )\n423:             continue\n424: \n425:         # Oversized paragraph — sentence-split into multiple sub-paragraphs.\n426:         if block.type == \"paragraph\" and block_tokens > hard_tokens:\n427:             _flush()\n428:             for sub in _split_oversized_paragraph(block.text, hard_tokens):\n429:                 sub_tokens = _count_tokens(sub)\n430:                 sections.append(\n431:                     Section(\n432:                         text=sub,\n433:                         breadcrumb=_current_breadcrumb(),\n434:                         token_count=sub_tokens,\n435:                         block_types=[\"paragraph\"],\n436:                     )\n437:                 )\n438:             continue\n439: \n440:         # Would adding this block exceed the soft cap? Close current first.\n441:         if current_tokens + block_tokens > soft_tokens and current_text_parts:\n442:             _flush()\n443: \n444:         current_text_parts.append(block.text)\n445:         current_tokens += block_tokens\n446:         current_types.append(block.type)\n447: \n448:     _flush()\n449:     return sections\n450: \n451: \n452: def doc_token_count(text: str) -> int:\n453:     \"\"\"Lightweight total-token estimate for the doc-refuse gate.\n454: \n\n(Showing lines 335-454 of 458. Use offset=455 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"def chunk_blocks(\n    blocks: list[Block],\n    *,\n    soft_tokens: int = SECTION_SOFT_TOKENS,\n    hard_tokens: int = SECTION_HARD_TOKENS,\n) -> list[Section]:\n    \"\"\"Greedy-pack typed blocks into Sections under token caps.\n\n    Section boundary triggers (in priority order):\n      1. A heading at depth ≤ 2 (H1/H2) AND the current accumulator is non-empty.\n         → close current section, start a new one with this heading.\n      2. Adding the next block would exceed ``soft_tokens``.\n         → close current section, the next block starts a new one.\n\n    Lists, tables, and code blocks are never split mid-element. If a\n    single such block exceeds ``hard_tokens`` on its own, it stands as\n    its own oversized section (the LLM handles oversized inputs better\n    than malformed half-tables).\n\n    Paragraphs that exceed ``hard_tokens`` alone get sentence-split via","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py","text":"def chunk_blocks(\n    blocks: list[Block],\n    *,\n    soft_tokens: int = SECTION_SOFT_TOKENS,\n    hard_tokens: int = SECTION_HARD_TOKENS,\n) -> list[Section]:\n    \"\"\"Greedy-pack typed blocks into Sections under token caps.\n\n    Section boundary triggers (in priority order):\n      1. A heading at depth ≤ 2 (H1/H2) AND the current accumulator is non-empty.\n         → close current section, start a new one with this heading.\n      2. Adding the next block would exceed ``soft_tokens``.\n         → close current section, the next block starts a new one.\n\n    Lists, tables, and code blocks are never split mid-element. If a\n    single such block exceeds ``hard_tokens`` on its own, it stands as\n    its own oversized section (the LLM handles oversized inputs better\n    than malformed half-tables).\n\n    Paragraphs that exceed ``hard_tokens`` alone get sentence-split via\n    pysbd into multiple sub-paragraphs, each its own paragraph block in\n    a new section.\n\n    The breadcrumb on each emitted Section reflects the most recent H1\n    and H2 (and H3 if shallow enough) encountered before that section.\n    Without headings (plain-text input), breadcrumb is \"\".\n    \"\"\"\n    sections: list[Section] = []\n    current_text_parts: list[str] = []\n    current_tokens = 0\n    current_types: list[BlockType] = []\n    # Breadcrumb tracking: stack of (depth, text) for the current heading trail\n    breadcrumb_stack: list[tuple[int, str]] = []\n\n    def _current_breadcrumb() -> str:\n        return \" > \".join(text for _, text in breadcrumb_stack)\n\n    def _flush() -> None:\n        nonlocal current_text_parts, current_tokens, current_types\n        if not current_text_parts:\n            return\n        joined = \"\\n\\n\".join(current_text_parts).strip()\n        if joined:\n            sections.append(\n                Section(\n                    text=joined,\n                    breadcrumb=_current_breadcrumb(),\n                    token_count=current_tokens,\n                    block_types=list(current_types),\n                )\n            )\n        current_text_parts = []\n        current_tokens = 0\n        current_types = []\n\n    for block in blocks:\n        block_tokens = _count_tokens(block.text)\n\n        if block.type == \"heading\":\n            # An H1/H2 closes the current section if non-empty. Flush\n            # BEFORE updating the heading stack so the prior section's\n            # breadcrumb reflects the OLD heading trail (the new heading\n            # belongs to the next section, not the one we're closing).\n            if block.depth <= 2 and current_text_parts:\n                _flush()\n            # Update breadcrumb stack: pop deeper-or-equal entries, push this one.\n            while breadcrumb_stack and breadcrumb_stack[-1][0] >= block.depth:\n                breadcrumb_stack.pop()\n            breadcrumb_stack.append((block.depth, block.text))\n            # The heading text itself goes into the next section as a\n            # rendered line (LLM benefits from seeing the heading).\n            current_text_parts.append((\"#\" * block.depth) + \" \" + block.text)\n            current_tokens += block_tokens\n            current_types.append(block.type)\n            continue\n\n        # Oversized atomic blocks (list/table/code) — emit as own section\n        # without splitting.\n        if block.type in (\"list\", \"table\", \"code\") and block_tokens > hard_tokens:\n            _flush()\n            sections.append(\n                Section(\n                    text=block.text,\n                    breadcrumb=_current_breadcrumb(),\n                    token_count=block_tokens,\n                    block_types=[block.type],\n                )\n            )\n            continue\n\n        # Oversized paragraph — sentence-split into multiple sub-paragraphs.\n        if block.type == \"paragraph\" and block_tokens > hard_tokens:\n            _flush()\n            for sub in _split_oversized_paragraph(block.text, hard_tokens):\n                sub_tokens = _count_tokens(sub)\n                sections.append(\n                    Section(\n                        text=sub,\n                        breadcrumb=_current_breadcrumb(),\n                        token_count=sub_tokens,\n                        block_types=[\"paragraph\"],\n                    )\n                )\n            continue\n\n        # Would adding this block exceed the soft cap? Close current first.\n        if current_tokens + block_tokens > soft_tokens and current_text_parts:\n            _flush()\n\n        current_text_parts.append(block.text)\n        current_tokens += block_tokens\n        current_types.append(block.type)\n\n    _flush()\n    return sections\n\n\ndef doc_token_count(text: str) -> int:\n    \"\"\"Lightweight total-token estimate for the doc-refuse gate.\n","lineStart":335,"lineEnd":454,"totalLines":458,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py","time":{"start":1780728145265,"end":1780728145280}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0664681595a21984016a23c1512edc8191b3762e2ca548c3f9"}},"id":"prt_e9bab2570001JRHRWZoGGL71AF","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","messageID":"msg_e9baaf730001FJHQVBg5JR83Sk"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728145282,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_3mNOOsVxv9uykw9vUY8POl6r","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py","offset":60,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n60:     ``text`` is the rendered content of the block as plain text. For\n61:     markdown headings we strip the leading ``#``s; for lists we render\n62:     each item on its own line; for code blocks we keep the body verbatim.\n63:     \"\"\"\n64: \n65:     type: BlockType\n66:     text: str\n67:     depth: int = 0\n68: \n69: \n70: @dataclass\n71: class Section:\n72:     \"\"\"A chunked unit produced by ``chunk_blocks`` — one LLM call per Section.\n73: \n74:     ``breadcrumb`` is the heading trail at this Section's position,\n75:     e.g. ``\"Release Notes > v2.3 > Performance\"``. Empty when the input\n76:     had no headings (plain-text path).\n77: \n78:     ``text`` is the joined plain-text content the LLM will see, NOT\n79:     including the breadcrumb (caller stitches the breadcrumb in via the\n80:     prompt as separate context).\n81: \n82:     ``token_count`` is the tiktoken-counted size of ``text``. Useful for\n83:     diagnostics and for the caller to refuse pathological docs early.\n84:     \"\"\"\n85: \n86:     text: str\n87:     breadcrumb: str = \"\"\n88:     token_count: int = 0\n89:     block_types: list[BlockType] = field(default_factory=list)\n90: \n91: \n92: # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n93: # Token counting — shared singleton encoder (creating the encoder is ~50ms)\n94: # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n95: \n96: \n97: _ENCODER: tiktoken.Encoding | None = None\n98: \n99: \n100: def _encoder() -> tiktoken.Encoding:\n101:     global _ENCODER\n102:     if _ENCODER is None:\n103:         # cl100k_base matches GPT-4 family. Close enough for size budgeting\n104:         # against newer models that use o200k_base — we're not optimizing\n105:         # for byte-precision, just keeping sections under ~2-3k tokens.\n106:         _ENCODER = tiktoken.get_encoding(\"cl100k_base\")\n107:     return _ENCODER\n108: \n109: \n110: def _count_tokens(text: str) -> int:\n111:     \"\"\"tiktoken cl100k_base count. Used by chunk_blocks for size caps.\"\"\"\n112:     return len(_encoder().encode(text))\n113: \n114: \n115: # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n116: # Parsers — format → list[Block]\n117: # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n118: \n119: \n120: # ``gfm-like`` enables tables (the only GFM addition we care about) plus\n121: # strikethrough and linkify. We disable linkify because it requires the\n122: # separate ``linkify-it-py`` dependency and we don't need URL auto-\n123: # detection for fact extraction.\n124: _md = MarkdownIt(\"gfm-like\", {\"breaks\": False, \"html\": False, \"linkify\": False})\n125: \n126: \n127: def parse_markdown(text: str) -> list[Block]:\n128:     \"\"\"Walk a markdown-it AST and emit a typed Block list.\n129: \n130:     Block types emitted:\n131:       - ``heading``: depth = 1..6, text = the heading body\n132:       - ``paragraph``: text = inline content\n133:       - ``list``: bullet/ordered items joined as ``\"- item\\\\n- item\"``\n134:       - ``code``: fenced or indented code blocks, body verbatim\n135:       - ``table``: rendered as plain-text rows\n136:       - ``blockquote``: text = inner content\n137: \n138:     Heading depth is preserved so the chunker can use H1/H2 as section\n139:     boundaries. Anything we don't recognize falls back to ``paragraph``.\n140:     \"\"\"\n141:     tokens = _md.parse(text)\n142:     blocks: list[Block] = []\n143: \n144:     i = 0\n145:     while i < len(tokens):\n146:         tok = tokens[i]\n147:         ttype = tok.type\n148: \n149:         if ttype == \"heading_open\":\n150:             depth = int(tok.tag[1])  # tag is \"h1\", \"h2\", ...\n151:             # heading_open → inline → heading_close\n152:             inline = tokens[i + 1]\n153:             body = (inline.content or \"\").strip()\n154:             if body:\n155:                 blocks.append(Block(type=\"heading\", text=body, depth=depth))\n156:             i += 3\n157:             continue\n158: \n159:         if ttype == \"paragraph_open\":\n160:             inline = tokens[i + 1]\n161:             body = (inline.content or \"\").strip()\n162:             if body:\n163:                 blocks.append(Block(type=\"paragraph\", text=body))\n164:             i += 3\n165:             continue\n166: \n167:         if ttype in (\"bullet_list_open\", \"ordered_list_open\"):\n168:             # Walk until the matching list_close, collecting the inline\n169:             # content of each list_item.\n170:             close = ttype.replace(\"_open\", \"_close\")\n171:             depth_stack = 1\n172:             items: list[str] = []\n173:             j = i + 1\n174:             while j < len(tokens) and depth_stack > 0:\n175:                 inner = tokens[j]\n176:                 if inner.type == ttype:\n177:                     depth_stack += 1\n178:                 elif inner.type == close:\n179:                     depth_stack -= 1\n\n(Showing lines 60-179 of 458. Use offset=180 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"    ``text`` is the rendered content of the block as plain text. For\n    markdown headings we strip the leading ``#``s; for lists we render\n    each item on its own line; for code blocks we keep the body verbatim.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    type: BlockType\n    text: str\n    depth: int = 0\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass Section:\n    \"\"\"A chunked unit produced by ``chunk_blocks`` — one LLM call per Section.\n\n    ``breadcrumb`` is the heading trail at this Section's position,\n    e.g. ``\"Release Notes > v2.3 > Performance\"``. Empty when the input\n    had no headings (plain-text path).\n\n    ``text`` is the joined plain-text content the LLM will see, NOT\n    including the breadcrumb (caller stitches the breadcrumb in via the","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py","text":"    ``text`` is the rendered content of the block as plain text. For\n    markdown headings we strip the leading ``#``s; for lists we render\n    each item on its own line; for code blocks we keep the body verbatim.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    type: BlockType\n    text: str\n    depth: int = 0\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass Section:\n    \"\"\"A chunked unit produced by ``chunk_blocks`` — one LLM call per Section.\n\n    ``breadcrumb`` is the heading trail at this Section's position,\n    e.g. ``\"Release Notes > v2.3 > Performance\"``. Empty when the input\n    had no headings (plain-text path).\n\n    ``text`` is the joined plain-text content the LLM will see, NOT\n    including the breadcrumb (caller stitches the breadcrumb in via the\n    prompt as separate context).\n\n    ``token_count`` is the tiktoken-counted size of ``text``. Useful for\n    diagnostics and for the caller to refuse pathological docs early.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    text: str\n    breadcrumb: str = \"\"\n    token_count: int = 0\n    block_types: list[BlockType] = field(default_factory=list)\n\n\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# Token counting — shared singleton encoder (creating the encoder is ~50ms)\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\n_ENCODER: tiktoken.Encoding | None = None\n\n\ndef _encoder() -> tiktoken.Encoding:\n    global _ENCODER\n    if _ENCODER is None:\n        # cl100k_base matches GPT-4 family. Close enough for size budgeting\n        # against newer models that use o200k_base — we're not optimizing\n        # for byte-precision, just keeping sections under ~2-3k tokens.\n        _ENCODER = tiktoken.get_encoding(\"cl100k_base\")\n    return _ENCODER\n\n\ndef _count_tokens(text: str) -> int:\n    \"\"\"tiktoken cl100k_base count. Used by chunk_blocks for size caps.\"\"\"\n    return len(_encoder().encode(text))\n\n\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# Parsers — format → list[Block]\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\n# ``gfm-like`` enables tables (the only GFM addition we care about) plus\n# strikethrough and linkify. We disable linkify because it requires the\n# separate ``linkify-it-py`` dependency and we don't need URL auto-\n# detection for fact extraction.\n_md = MarkdownIt(\"gfm-like\", {\"breaks\": False, \"html\": False, \"linkify\": False})\n\n\ndef parse_markdown(text: str) -> list[Block]:\n    \"\"\"Walk a markdown-it AST and emit a typed Block list.\n\n    Block types emitted:\n      - ``heading``: depth = 1..6, text = the heading body\n      - ``paragraph``: text = inline content\n      - ``list``: bullet/ordered items joined as ``\"- item\\\\n- item\"``\n      - ``code``: fenced or indented code blocks, body verbatim\n      - ``table``: rendered as plain-text rows\n      - ``blockquote``: text = inner content\n\n    Heading depth is preserved so the chunker can use H1/H2 as section\n    boundaries. Anything we don't recognize falls back to ``paragraph``.\n    \"\"\"\n    tokens = _md.parse(text)\n    blocks: list[Block] = []\n\n    i = 0\n    while i < len(tokens):\n        tok = tokens[i]\n        ttype = tok.type\n\n        if ttype == \"heading_open\":\n            depth = int(tok.tag[1])  # tag is \"h1\", \"h2\", ...\n            # heading_open → inline → heading_close\n            inline = tokens[i + 1]\n            body = (inline.content or \"\").strip()\n            if body:\n                blocks.append(Block(type=\"heading\", text=body, depth=depth))\n            i += 3\n            continue\n\n        if ttype == \"paragraph_open\":\n            inline = tokens[i + 1]\n            body = (inline.content or \"\").strip()\n            if body:\n                blocks.append(Block(type=\"paragraph\", text=body))\n            i += 3\n            continue\n\n        if ttype in (\"bullet_list_open\", \"ordered_list_open\"):\n            # Walk until the matching list_close, collecting the inline\n            # content of each list_item.\n            close = ttype.replace(\"_open\", \"_close\")\n            depth_stack = 1\n            items: list[str] = []\n            j = i + 1\n            while j < len(tokens) and depth_stack > 0:\n                inner = tokens[j]\n                if inner.type == ttype:\n                    depth_stack += 1\n                elif inner.type == close:\n                    depth_stack -= 1","lineStart":60,"lineEnd":179,"totalLines":458,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py","time":{"start":1780728145263,"end":1780728145281}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0664681595a21984016a23c1512ebc8191addad5475e8a0b11"}},"id":"prt_e9bab256a001oLbxiGAZii4Axh","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","messageID":"msg_e9baaf730001FJHQVBg5JR83Sk"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780728145288,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_YiYOxqS2QN0Ygz0QUTyuZGJS","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_service.py","offset":255,"limit":90},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n255: async def _chunk_content(\n256:     text: str,\n257:     focus: str | None = None,\n258:     tenant_config=None,\n259:     breadcrumb: str | None = None,\n260: ) -> list[dict]:\n261:     \"\"\"Extract atomic facts from text via LLM.\n262: \n263:     The chunker module produces section-sized text up to ~3k tokens;\n264:     callers pass each section here. The optional ``breadcrumb`` is the\n265:     heading trail of where this section sits in its source document\n266:     (e.g. ``\"Release Notes > v2.3 > Performance\"``) and gets injected\n267:     into the prompt as separate context so the LLM can disambiguate\n268:     references like \"this release\" or \"the migration\".\n269: \n270:     ``breadcrumb`` is the only addition; everything else (focus, meta-fact\n271:     filter, salience floor, short-fact filter) is unchanged from PR #5.\n272:     \"\"\"\n273:     provider_name = (\n274:         tenant_config.enrichment_provider if tenant_config else None\n275:     ) or settings.entity_extraction_provider\n276: \n277:     focus_instruction = \"\"\n278:     if focus:\n279:         focus_instruction = f\"Focus on facts relevant to {focus}. Deprioritize unrelated details.\"\n280: \n281:     breadcrumb_instruction = \"\"\n282:     if breadcrumb:\n283:         breadcrumb_instruction = (\n284:             f\"\\n## Document context\\n\\nThis section appears under: {breadcrumb}\\n\"\n285:             \"Use this trail to resolve ambiguous references (e.g. 'this version', \"\n286:             \"'the migration') when extracting facts.\\n\"\n287:         )\n288: \n289:     prompt = CHUNKING_PROMPT.format(\n290:         content=text,\n291:         focus_instruction=focus_instruction,\n292:         breadcrumb_instruction=breadcrumb_instruction,\n293:     )\n294: \n295:     async def _do_chunk(llm):\n296:         return await llm.complete_json(prompt)\n297: \n298:     raw = await call_with_fallback(\n299:         primary_provider_name=provider_name,\n300:         call_fn=_do_chunk,\n301:         fake_fn=_fake_ingest,\n302:         tenant_config=tenant_config,\n303:         service_label=\"ingest\",\n304:     )\n305: \n306:     # Validate: must be a list of objects with \"content\"\n307:     facts: list[dict] = []\n308:     if isinstance(raw, dict):\n309:         # Handle {\"facts\": [...]} wrapper\n310:         for v in raw.values():\n311:             if isinstance(v, list):\n312:                 raw = v\n313:                 break\n314:     dropped_meta = 0\n315:     dropped_low_salience = 0\n316:     dropped_short = 0\n317:     for item in raw:\n318:         if not isinstance(item, dict) or not item.get(\"content\"):\n319:             continue\n320:         body = str(item[\"content\"]).strip()\n321: \n322:         # P2.4: drop facts that describe the input rather than extract\n323:         # from it. Prompt forbids them but the LLM still produces them\n324:         # occasionally — especially on short/trivial input.\n325:         if _META_FACT_RE.search(body):\n326:             dropped_meta += 1\n327:             continue\n328: \n329:         # A5: drop sub-5-word fragments. Prompt forbids them but the LLM\n330:         # still emits short headings/labels on noisy inputs.\n331:         if len(body.split()) < _MIN_FACT_WORDS:\n332:             dropped_short += 1\n333:             continue\n334: \n335:         # A1: drop low-salience facts. The LLM emits a per-fact 0-1\n336:         # salience score (see CHUNKING_PROMPT); anything below the floor\n337:         # is dropped without ever reaching the write pipeline.\n338:         salience_raw = item.get(\"salience\")\n339:         try:\n340:             salience = float(salience_raw) if salience_raw is not None else None\n341:         except (TypeError, ValueError):\n342:             salience = None\n343:         if salience is not None and salience < _SALIENCE_FLOOR:\n344:             dropped_low_salience += 1\n\n(Showing lines 255-344 of 1153. Use offset=345 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"async def _chunk_content(\n    text: str,\n    focus: str | None = None,\n    tenant_config=None,\n    breadcrumb: str | None = None,\n) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"Extract atomic facts from text via LLM.\n\n    The chunker module produces section-sized text up to ~3k tokens;\n    callers pass each section here. The optional ``breadcrumb`` is the\n    heading trail of where this section sits in its source document\n    (e.g. ``\"Release Notes > v2.3 > Performance\"``) and gets injected\n    into the prompt as separate context so the LLM can disambiguate\n    references like \"this release\" or \"the migration\".\n\n    ``breadcrumb`` is the only addition; everything else (focus, meta-fact\n    filter, salience floor, short-fact filter) is unchanged from PR #5.\n    \"\"\"\n    provider_name = (\n        tenant_config.enrichment_provider if tenant_config else None","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_service.py","text":"async def _chunk_content(\n    text: str,\n    focus: str | None = None,\n    tenant_config=None,\n    breadcrumb: str | None = None,\n) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"Extract atomic facts from text via LLM.\n\n    The chunker module produces section-sized text up to ~3k tokens;\n    callers pass each section here. The optional ``breadcrumb`` is the\n    heading trail of where this section sits in its source document\n    (e.g. ``\"Release Notes > v2.3 > Performance\"``) and gets injected\n    into the prompt as separate context so the LLM can disambiguate\n    references like \"this release\" or \"the migration\".\n\n    ``breadcrumb`` is the only addition; everything else (focus, meta-fact\n    filter, salience floor, short-fact filter) is unchanged from PR #5.\n    \"\"\"\n    provider_name = (\n        tenant_config.enrichment_provider if tenant_config else None\n    ) or settings.entity_extraction_provider\n\n    focus_instruction = \"\"\n    if focus:\n        focus_instruction = f\"Focus on facts relevant to {focus}. Deprioritize unrelated details.\"\n\n    breadcrumb_instruction = \"\"\n    if breadcrumb:\n        breadcrumb_instruction = (\n            f\"\\n## Document context\\n\\nThis section appears under: {breadcrumb}\\n\"\n            \"Use this trail to resolve ambiguous references (e.g. 'this version', \"\n            \"'the migration') when extracting facts.\\n\"\n        )\n\n    prompt = CHUNKING_PROMPT.format(\n        content=text,\n        focus_instruction=focus_instruction,\n        breadcrumb_instruction=breadcrumb_instruction,\n    )\n\n    async def _do_chunk(llm):\n        return await llm.complete_json(prompt)\n\n    raw = await call_with_fallback(\n        primary_provider_name=provider_name,\n        call_fn=_do_chunk,\n        fake_fn=_fake_ingest,\n        tenant_config=tenant_config,\n        service_label=\"ingest\",\n    )\n\n    # Validate: must be a list of objects with \"content\"\n    facts: list[dict] = []\n    if isinstance(raw, dict):\n        # Handle {\"facts\": [...]} wrapper\n        for v in raw.values():\n            if isinstance(v, list):\n                raw = v\n                break\n    dropped_meta = 0\n    dropped_low_salience = 0\n    dropped_short = 0\n    for item in raw:\n        if not isinstance(item, dict) or not item.get(\"content\"):\n            continue\n        body = str(item[\"content\"]).strip()\n\n        # P2.4: drop facts that describe the input rather than extract\n        # from it. Prompt forbids them but the LLM still produces them\n        # occasionally — especially on short/trivial input.\n        if _META_FACT_RE.search(body):\n            dropped_meta += 1\n            continue\n\n        # A5: drop sub-5-word fragments. Prompt forbids them but the LLM\n        # still emits short headings/labels on noisy inputs.\n        if len(body.split()) < _MIN_FACT_WORDS:\n            dropped_short += 1\n            continue\n\n        # A1: drop low-salience facts. The LLM emits a per-fact 0-1\n        # salience score (see CHUNKING_PROMPT); anything below the floor\n        # is dropped without ever reaching the write pipeline.\n        salience_raw = item.get(\"salience\")\n        try:\n            salience = float(salience_raw) if salience_raw is not None else None\n        except (TypeError, ValueError):\n            salience = None\n        if salience is not None and salience < _SALIENCE_FLOOR:\n            dropped_low_salience += 1","lineStart":255,"lineEnd":344,"totalLines":1153,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_service.py","time":{"start":1780728145256,"end":1780728145286}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0664681595a21984016a23c1512ea8819180b5ff509dfde4cb"}},"id":"prt_e9bab2549001ZLrpFCCOcF4001","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","messageID":"msg_e9baaf730001FJHQVBg5JR83Sk"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780728145577,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"id":"prt_e9bab26a6001FxrkLbKkhNMFfU","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"24fcd20f0ca1d4779f95a5e438f8ef3426e22ebb","messageID":"msg_e9baaf730001FJHQVBg5JR83Sk","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":87707,"input":5747,"output":503,"reasoning":49,"cache":{"write":0,"read":81408}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780728147116,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"id":"prt_e9bab2cab001VrjLWldBHXwhdk","messageID":"msg_e9bab27af001GjIgOkvoB66YYA","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","snapshot":"dd83d8eb2d58f8e66cd636d4a48bae2ba5bfde81","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1780728208171,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"id":"prt_e9bab52d8001odHY6HgQ6LHc5q","messageID":"msg_e9bab27af001GjIgOkvoB66YYA","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","type":"text","text":"## Mechanism\nChunking: MemClaw has two “split into smaller memory units” paths, not a general chunk-fingerprint incremental index. Large ingest/direct writes use a structure-aware chunker: `Section` carries `text`, `breadcrumb`, `token_count`, and block types (`core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py:70`), markdown parsing preserves headings/lists/code/tables (`core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py:127`), and `chunk_blocks()` greedily closes sections on H1/H2 boundaries or soft-token overflow while preserving lists/tables/code as atomic blocks (`core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py:335`). Each section then goes through LLM fact extraction via `_chunk_content()`, with breadcrumb context injected into the prompt (`core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_service.py:255`). Enrichment also has `atomic_facts`: the prompt asks for separate child facts only when distinct claims would be searched by different vocabulary (`common/enrichment/_prompts.py:127`), and the schema says each fact becomes a child memory with its own embedding (`common/enrichment/schema.py:50`).\n\nEmbedding trigger/versioning: write mode controls whether embedding/enrichment happen inline or are deferred. Strong writes embed and enrich inline; fast writes always defer enrichment and may defer embedding depending on deployment settings (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/parallel_embed_enrich.py:7`). Deferred embedding publishes `EMBED_REQUESTED` with `memory_id`, `tenant_id`, `content`, and optional `content_hash` (`common/events/memory_embed_publisher.py:21`; `common/events/memory_embed_request.py:21`). `_schedule_embed_or_reembed()` chooses inline `_reembed_memory()` or publishes the event (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:1544`). MemClaw has provider/model/dimension configuration, but not durable per-row embedding model versioning in the embed request: `MemoryEmbedRequest` contains only identity, tenant, content, and content_hash (`common/events/memory_embed_request.py:38`). Model/dim are process/env/schema concerns: `VECTOR_DIM = 1024` (`common/constants.py:3`), OpenAI model comes from `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_MODEL` (`common/embedding/constants.py:21`), and the registry validates base-url/dim/truncation compatibility (`common/embedding/_registry.py:267`). Docs say provider switches do not require migration if schema dim stays fixed, though re-embed may be desirable for vector-space consistency (`docs/local-embedder.md:307`).\n\nIdempotent re-embed: deferred embedding is explicitly at-least-once safe: a redelivered event re-PATCHes the same deterministic embedding, and `content_hash` avoids duplicate provider calls (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:25`). The worker first looks up an existing embedding by content_hash and reuses it on hit (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:144`), while storage lookup failures degrade to “miss” rather than nacking (`core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:134`). The PATCH clears `metadata.embedding_pending=false` in the same storage update (`core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:187`). Inline `_reembed_memory()` retries with backoff and refuses to overwrite an embedding already present, treating that as a race guard (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:1723`; `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:1750`).\n\nEnrichment schema + flow: `EnrichmentResult` includes `memory_type`, `weight`, `title`, `summary`, `tags`, `status`, temporal bounds, PII fields, `retrieval_hint`, `atomic_facts`, and `llm_ms` (`common/enrichment/schema.py:64`). The prompt is the schema source and defines retrieval hints as query-vocabulary augmentation metadata, plus atomic facts as optional child-memory candidates (`common/enrichment/_prompts.py:108`; `common/enrichment/_prompts.py:127`). `enrich_memory()` runs a provider/fallback chain and “never raises”; it always returns an `EnrichmentResult` or heuristic fallback (`common/enrichment/service.py:272`). The worker routes ORM fields and metadata fields through explicit allowlists and import-time exhaustiveness checks (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:217`; `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:284`). Redelivered enrichment skips agent-provided fields (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:368`), uses `llm_ms > 0` to prevent heuristic fallback from clearing real LLM-derived fields (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:393`; `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:445`), clears `enrichment_pending`, PATCHes storage, then publishes `ENRICHED` best-effort (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:431`; `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:473`; `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:555`). Important correction: hint-based re-embedding is disabled because it made write vectors use hinted text while queries used raw text, hurting recall; both hot path and background now embed raw content (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/parallel_embed_enrich.py:29`; `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2094`).\n\n## Teachings for Spec Kit Memory (027/003)\n1. **Claim** · Keep a durable per-chunk fingerprint/cache gate before embedding, but scope it to local chunk identity rather than tenant/content-only hashes. **Evidence** · MemClaw hashes tenant/fleet/content (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:91`), sends content_hash in embed requests (`common/events/memory_embed_request.py:31`), and the worker reuses cached embeddings on content_hash hit (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:144`). **Maps-to** · 027/003. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Over-broad hashes can reuse embeddings across semantically different chunk contexts; under-broad hashes miss reuse. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit Memory already has chunk fingerprints; the transferable lesson is the idempotent “fingerprint hit skips embed” gate, not MemClaw’s tenant/fleet hash shape.\n\n2. **Claim** · Persist explicit “pending/stale/cleared” embedding/enrichment state transitions in metadata, not just absence of a vector. **Evidence** · MemClaw clears `embedding_pending` when the worker PATCHes the vector (`core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:187`) and clears `enrichment_pending` after enrichment succeeds (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:431`). **Maps-to** · 027/003. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Extra state can become inconsistent unless updates are atomic with vector/enrichment writes. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · A local SQLite/vector-store pipeline still benefits from resumable “dirty/pending/complete” state, but it should be one local transaction or a recoverable two-store commit marker, not Pub/Sub status.\n\n3. **Claim** · Add durable embedding provenance/version fields even though MemClaw mostly lacks them per row. **Evidence** · MemClaw’s embed request has no provider/model/version fields (`common/events/memory_embed_request.py:38`), while provider/model/dim are resolved from env/schema (`common/embedding/constants.py:21`; `common/constants.py:3`) and docs note provider switches may justify re-embedding for vector-space consistency (`docs/local-embedder.md:307`). **Maps-to** · 027/003 or new sub-packet. **Verdict** · ADOPT. **Risk** · Schema churn and unnecessary re-embed if version semantics are too sensitive. **Confidence** · Medium. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit Memory’s embedder is fixed to ollama nomic 768d, so this should not support model swapping; it should record `embedder_id`, `dim=768`, prompt/text-shape version, and enrichment/schema version so stale rows are detectable after pipeline changes.\n\n4. **Claim** · Do not embed retrieval-hint-prefixed content unless query embeddings use the same surface; store hints as retrieval metadata instead. **Evidence** · MemClaw explicitly removed hint-based re-embed because hinted write text vs raw query text reduced identical content-query cosine similarity and capped recall (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/parallel_embed_enrich.py:158`); inline enrichment now persists retrieval_hint only for debugging/auditability, not embedding shape (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2063`). **Maps-to** · 027/003. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Pure raw-content embeddings may miss concept-level queries that a hint could help. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · With fixed nomic-768d, keep chunk text as the embedding source unless Spec Kit also applies the same augmentation to queries or stores a separate hint vector/channel.\n\n5. **Claim** · Use explicit enrichment field routing and “real enrichment vs fallback” guards before mutating indexed metadata. **Evidence** · MemClaw separates ORM enrichment fields from metadata fields (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:217`), fails import on unrouted schema fields (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:284`), skips agent-provided fields on redelivery (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:368`), and uses `llm_ms > 0` to stop heuristic fallback from clearing real LLM metadata (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:445`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet. **Verdict** · ADOPT. **Risk** · If fallback markers are unreliable, stale metadata may be preserved or good fallback output may be ignored. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit Memory can reuse the principle locally: only deterministic/validated enrichment should update searchable metadata; fallback/heuristic enrichment should not erase stronger prior values.\n\n## Negative knowledge\nDo not copy Pub/Sub worker topology, at-least-once delivery machinery, DLQs, per-tenant concurrency slots, tenant config payloads, or encrypted credential-on-event patterns. Those exist because MemClaw is fleet/multi-tenant and distributed (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:31`; `common/events/memory_enrich_request.py:10`; `core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:544`).\n\nDo not copy pgvector/VECTOR_DIM migration logic or model-switch guidance as a feature direction. Spec Kit Memory’s embedder is fixed to ollama nomic 768d. MemClaw’s `VECTOR_DIM=1024`, TEI/bge-m3 defaults, truncation knobs, and provider-switch docs are negative knowledge except for the general need to record dimension/provenance (`common/constants.py:3`; `docs/local-embedder.md:271`; `common/embedding/_registry.py:312`).\n\nDo not copy hint-prefixed re-embedding. MemClaw tried it and removed it because it created write/query embedding-surface asymmetry (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/parallel_embed_enrich.py:29`).\n\nDo not copy tenant-scoped content hashes directly. Spec Kit Memory needs local file/chunk identity, line spans, chunk kind, content fingerprint, dependency DAG inputs, and embedder/schema version, not `tenant_id:fleet_id:content` (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:91`).\n\nDo not treat MemClaw’s async worker atomic-fact gap as a pattern to emulate. The worker explicitly logs that async child-memory creation is not implemented (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:520`), while the synchronous path creates child memories with embeddings (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2105`).\n\n## Open questions\nDoes Spec Kit Memory 027/003 already persist an embedding provenance tuple separate from chunk fingerprint, or only content/chunk fingerprints?\n\nShould enrichment outputs affect vector text, lexical metadata only, or a separate rerank/scoring channel for local search?\n\nCan the SQLite index and separate vector store support an atomic “embedding_pending → embedded” transition, or is a repair scan needed for torn two-store writes?\n\nShould line-span and dependency-DAG changes trigger re-enrichment independently from re-embedding, or should enrichment be keyed only on chunk text fingerprint?\n\nShould structure-aware chunking from MemClaw’s H1/H2/soft-token design inform Spec Kit Memory docs/spec chunking, or is 027/003’s chunk-kind/line-span design already sufficient?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"085\",\"focus\":\"indexing / embedding / enrichment pipeline\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.78,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: fingerprint-gated idempotent embedding reuse for local chunk identities\",\"ADAPT: pending/stale state transitions without distributed worker machinery\",\"ADOPT: durable embedding provenance despite fixed nomic-768d\",\"ADAPT: store retrieval hints as metadata, not hinted write vectors\",\"ADOPT: explicit enrichment routing and fallback guards\"],\"sources\":[\"core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:144\",\"core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/parallel_embed_enrich.py:158\",\"common/events/memory_embed_request.py:38\",\"common/enrichment/schema.py:64\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/ingest_chunking.py:335\"]}","time":{"start":1780728156888,"end":1780728208169},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_03e52a386ae109bb016a23c15cde0881919b1c3f9c5b1fbf99","phase":"final_answer"}}}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780728208485,"sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","part":{"id":"prt_e9bac1c63001gw3pG3V6NkR11s","reason":"stop","snapshot":"bb2c1177792eeef29da5a3f124dd69f9ac206078","messageID":"msg_e9bab27af001GjIgOkvoB66YYA","sessionID":"ses_164567591ffeXwPyQE0CKtQKNY","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":96814,"input":6415,"output":2843,"reasoning":516,"cache":{"write":0,"read":87040}},"cost":0}}
